{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"717ca7f2-d29c-4abf-9ecb-93c97356bbe8","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, so here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a **dotnet tool**:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server over stdio</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n1. **`PackAsTool`** — marks the project as a .NET tool.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will run (e.g. `my-mcp-server`).\n3. **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — tools must be console apps.\n\n### Publish workflow\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push (requires a NuGet API key)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\n```\n\nThat's the minimum. Optionally add `PackageProjectUrl`, `RepositoryUrl`, and `PackageTags` for better discoverability.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f1c83853-6096-4ca9-95be-f6b822aaa05b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory doesn't exist yet. The user is asking what they need to configure, not asking me to do it. Let me give them the guidance they need.","outputTokens":482},"id":"b862ddcc-de1c-4667-9e03-c43953c51e2a","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:46:11.457Z","parentId":"49838978-432a-4599-9122-fdf337c628de"}
